[32] In my view, the facts of this case do not render the circumstances that Clover finds itself in to be unfair. The CLP agreement makes it quite clear precisely on what the Commission was prepared to grant Clover conditional immunity and in respect of and what would still form part of the original investigation. It was with full knowledge that the Commission still intended to investigate a possible abuse of dominance by Clover based on the sales of Cquota milk that Clover entered into the CLP agreement. It is clear form the CLP document that the Commission regarded the conduct underlying the third complaint as separate and distinct from the conduct underlying the sixth complaint. Clover no doubt was aware of this. Clover must have been aware that it might well find itself in a position of having to cooperate with the Commission on one complaint referral and face prosecution on another.}
